# Invoice Brain — Cursor Rules

## Project Context
This is a Laravel 12 demo application showcasing the first-party Laravel MCP integration.
The app is a billing/invoicing tool where an AI assistant (Claude via MCP) can
read billing state and take actions through typed MCP tools and resources.

Package: `laravel/mcp` — first-party, ships with Laravel 12. Always refer to this for MCP patterns.

---

## Laravel Conventions

- PHP 8.3+ syntax always: typed properties, match expressions, readonly where applicable
- Models use `$fillable` not `$guarded`
- Always use `->value()` on Enums when storing to DB
- Money/amounts are ALWAYS stored in cents (integer). Never floats for money.
- Dates use Carbon. Always return `Carbon` instances from model accessors.
- Use Form Requests for all HTTP validation
- Use Resource classes (`JsonResource`) for all API responses
- Services go in `app/Services/`, one responsibility per service
- No logic in Controllers — delegate to Services

## Database

- Database: SQLite (file: `database/database.sqlite`)
- Migrations: always add `->comment()` to non-obvious columns
- Always define `down()` in migrations properly
- Foreign keys always have `->constrained()->cascadeOnDelete()` unless noted
- `status` columns use PHP-backed Enums — define them in `app/Enums/`

## MCP Specific Rules

- MCP Server class lives at `app/Mcp/Servers/InvoiceBrainServer.php`, extends `Laravel\Mcp\Server`
- All Tool classes live in `app/Mcp/Tools/`, extend `Laravel\Mcp\Server\Tool`
- All Resource classes live in `app/Mcp/Resources/`, extend `Laravel\Mcp\Server\Resource`
- Tools and Resources are registered in the Server class `$tools` and `$resources` arrays
- The server is mounted in `routes/ai.php` — NOT `routes/mcp.php` or `routes/web.php`

- Every Tool MUST have:
  - `protected string $description` — written for Claude to read, not humans
  - `public function schema(JsonSchema $schema): array` — fluent schema definition
  - `public function handle(Request $request): Response` — the action
  - Be explicit in descriptions about when to use this tool vs similar tools

- Every Resource MUST have:
  - `protected string $description` — what data this exposes
  - `public function handle(Request $request): string` — returns JSON string
  - The JSON string MUST include a `summary` key with a single prose sentence

- Tools use `$request->validate([...])` for input validation (same as HTTP requests)
- Tools return `Response::text('...')` for success, `Response::error('...')` for failure
- Resources return `Response::text(json_encode([...]))` — a string, not an array
- Never throw exceptions from MCP tools or resources — use `Response::error()`
- Tool names use snake_case via `#[Name('create_invoice')]` attribute or `$name` property
- Resource URIs follow pattern: `{noun}://list`, `{noun}://{id}`, `{noun}://filter`

## Naming Conventions

- Controllers: `ClientController`, `InvoiceController`
- Models: singular `Client`, `Invoice`, `WorkLog`
- MCP Tools: `CreateInvoiceTool`, `SendPaymentReminderTool`
- MCP Resources: `ClientResource`, `InvoiceResource` (prefix with `Mcp` if conflicts with JsonResource)
- Enums: `InvoiceStatus`, `InvoicePriority`
- Services: `InvoiceNumberService`, `InvoicePdfService`
- Mail: `InvoiceMail`, `PaymentReminderMail`

## Code Style

- No commented-out code
- No `var_dump`, `dd()`, `dump()` left in committed code (use `ray()` or log)
- Explicit return types on all methods
- DocBlocks only when the type system can't express it
- Prefer early returns over nested if-else
- Collections over array_* functions always

## Blade / Frontend

- Tailwind CSS utility classes only — no custom CSS files
- Alpine.js for interactivity — no jQuery, no Vue, no React
- All layouts extend `layouts.app`
- Flash messages use `session('success')` and `session('error')`
- Money display: always format cents → human readable via a `@money` Blade directive
  defined in `AppServiceProvider`

## Testing

- Pest for all tests
- Feature tests for MCP tools: assert DB state changed + return value is correct
- Never test implementation details — test behaviour
- Use `RefreshDatabase` trait
- Factories for all models — always

## Do Not

- Do not install `php-mcp/laravel` — the first-party `laravel/mcp` is already included
- Do not use `php-open-source-saver/phpqrcode` or similar — we don't need QR codes
- Do not install Livewire — Blade + Alpine is sufficient for this demo
- Do not add API authentication — this is a local demo app
- Do not use UUIDs — integer IDs are fine for a demo
- Do not store computed values that can be derived (e.g. invoice `overdue` status)
- Do not add soft deletes unless explicitly specified
